        But, simply put, I find it difficult to maintain a confidence that the ultimate in light of our most current knowledge from the field of physics.
        -->
      </p>
      <br>
      <p>
        This is a more practical problem for researchers than the idea that it is worth knowing our history (which I also believe to be true).
      </p>
      <br>
      <p>
        The second <i>deleterious effect</i> of the hole in human culture is that while these <i>potholes</i> remain unfilled,
        there is a not emptiness but a fragile structure which threatens the integrity of the knowledge piled above.
      </p>
      <br>
      <p>
        Our knowledge is not grounded on the researcher and their individual understanding.
        Simply put, we collectively know too much. Our knowledge leans back on itself,
        and it is nearly impossible to tell whether any particular fact we rely on is well founded without climbing the whole mountain over again.
        As a result, out of necessity, we employ facts we do not know.
      </p>
